body:
**BEE2 version:** 4.38.1

I'm writing a VDF serializer in Rust, and while looking for source files to glean the format from I noticed a discrepancy between BEE's `editoritems.txt` and `editoritems_original.txt.` BEE seems to increase the indentation level before writing the opening `{` and decrease it after writing the `}`. Both of these are reversed from the way Valve does it.

`editoritems_original.txt` starts like this. Notice how the `{` matches the indentation level of the key preceding it, and is one level shallower than the keys inside the block.
```
"ItemData"
{
	"Item"
	{
		"ItemClass"		"ItemPedestalButton"
		"Type"			"ITEM_BUTTON_PEDESTAL"
		"Editor"
		{
			"SubType"
			{
				"Name"		"PORTAL2_PuzzleEditor_Item_pedestal_button"
				"Model"
				{
					"ModelName"		"switch.3ds"
					"TextureName"	"buttonpedestal.png"
				}
```

The BEE-generated `editoritems.txt` starts like this. Notice how the `{` is one level deeper than the key preceding it, and is at the same level as the keys inside the block. In my opinion, this is a lot harder to read than Valve's file.
```
"ItemData"
	{
	"Item"
		{
		"Type" "ITEM_POINT_LIGHT"
		"Exporting"
			{
			"Instances"
				{
				"0"
					{
					"Name" "instances/BEE2/clean/point_light.vmf"
					"EntityCount" "0"
					}
				}
			"TargetName" "plight"
			"Offset" "64 64 64"
			}
```

You can also see how bee-generated editoritems files end with an indented `}`, but Valve's just end with a `}` on its own line.
